<HEADLINE>
<P>
NON-JAPANESE CUSTOM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In regards to the article "The Turning Point" (by Itabari Njeri, Jan. 1) about 
the Japanese-Americans' concern over their culture's future. As a 
third-generation Japanese-American, I found this article to be somewhat 
overblown. 
</P>
<P>
My father was in a relocation camp and my parents are Buddhists. I'm 
non-religious. My wife and I do not observe any Japanese customs in our 
household and we will not force our two small children to attend Saturday 
morning Japanese-language school as many of our peers were forced to do by 
well-meaning parents. 
</P>
<P>
My children will most likely marry Caucasians and our grandchildren will be of 
mixed blood. We will not pressure them to marry in the same ethnic class as 
many Nisei and Issei parents have done to their children. Our major concern is 
that our children grow up happy and successful. If they want to learn about 
their heritage and culture, they will do so on their own. 
</P>
<P>
HENRY SAKAIDA 
</P>
<P>
Temple City 
</P>
</TEXT>
